College Success Predictors: A Machine Learning Approach¶

Project Overview¶

This project aims to apply machine learning techniques to analyze the College Scorecard data from the U.S. Department of Education. The primary objective is to identify key university-level factors that predict strong retention and graduation rates. By understanding these factors, educational institutions can better target their efforts to improve student outcomes.

Blogpost found here - https://medium.com/@justinesylivera/uncovering-the-secrets-of-student-success-a-machine-learning-journey-6c89336220a3¶

Objectives:¶

  1. Perform descriptive analysis to understand the distributions and relationships within the data.
  2. Conduct exploratory analysis to identify potential patterns and correlations.
  3. Use machine learning models to predict retention and graduation rates.
  4. Analyze feature importance to identify the most significant predictors of these outcomes.

Dataset:¶

The dataset used in this project is the College Scorecard data provided by the U.S. Department of Education. It contains comprehensive information about U.S. colleges and universities, including attributes such as:

  • Tuition fees
  • Student loan amounts
  • Retention rates
  • Graduation rates
  • Student demographics
  • Institutional characteristics

Main Tasks:¶

  1. Data Preprocessing: Load the dataset, handle missing values, and prepare the data for analysis.
  2. Descriptive Analysis: Generate summary statistics and visualizations to understand the data.
  3. Exploratory Analysis: Explore relationships between different variables using plots and correlation matrices.
  4. Predictive Modeling: Train machine learning models to predict retention and graduation rates.
  5. Feature Importance: Analyze the importance of different features in predicting the outcomes.

Metrics:¶

The models will be evaluated using the following metrics:

  • Mean Absolute Error (MAE): Measures the average magnitude of errors in the predictions.
  • Mean Squared Error (MSE): Measures the average squared difference between actual and predicted values.
  • R-squared (R²): Indicates the proportion of variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variables.

Table of Contents¶

I. Exploratory Data Analysis
II. Predictive Analytics(modelling)
III. Conclusion

# Calculate the correlation matrix
corr_matrix = features.corr()

# Filter the correlation matrix to include only correlations greater than 0.60 or less than -0.60
filtered_corr = corr_matrix[(corr_matrix >= 0.60) | (corr_matrix <= -0.60)]

# Drop rows and columns where all values are NaN
filtered_corr = filtered_corr.dropna(how='all').dropna(axis=1, how='all')

# Generate a mask for the upper triangle
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(filtered_corr, dtype=bool))

# Set up the matplotlib figure
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))

# Draw the heatmap with the mask and correct aspect ratio
sns.heatmap(filtered_corr, mask=mask, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', vmin=-1, vmax=1, center=0, linewidths=0.5, fmt='.2f', cbar_kws={"shrink": 0.75})

plt.title('Correlation Matrix for Correlations Greater Than 0.60 (Lower Triangle Only)')
plt.show()

# Split the data for graduation rate prediction
X_train_grad, X_test_grad, y_train_grad, y_test_grad = train_test_split(features_, target_graduation, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Split the data for retention rate prediction
X_train_ret, X_test_ret, y_train_ret, y_test_ret = train_test_split(features_, target_retention, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Define the parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'num_leaves': [31, 50],
    'learning_rate': [0.1, 0.01],
    'n_estimators': [100, 200]
}
# Initialize the LightGBM model
model = lgb.LGBMRegressor(random_state=42)

# Initialize GridSearchCV for graduation rate
grid_search_grad = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=param_grid, cv=3, scoring='r2', verbose=1, n_jobs=-1)
grid_search_grad.fit(X_train_grad, y_train_grad, categorical_feature=categorical_features)

# Best parameters found by GridSearchCV for graduation rate
print('Best parameters for graduation rate model:', grid_search_grad.best_params_)

# Predict on the test set with the best estimator for graduation rate
best_model_grad = grid_search_grad.best_estimator_
y_pred_grad = best_model_grad.predict(X_test_grad)

# Evaluate the model for graduation rate
mae_grad = mean_absolute_error(y_test_grad, y_pred_grad)
mse_grad = mean_squared_error(y_test_grad, y_pred_grad)
r2_grad = r2_score(y_test_grad, y_pred_grad)

print('Graduation Rate Model with Grid Search')
print('MAE:', mae_grad)
print('MSE:', mse_grad)
print('R^2:', r2_grad)

# Function to plot top 10 feature importances
def plot_top_10_features(importances, feature_names, title):
    # Get indices of top 10 features
    indices = np.argsort(importances)[-10:]
    top_features = [feature_names[i] for i in indices]
    top_importances = importances[indices]
    
    # Sort the features by importance
    sorted_indices = np.argsort(top_importances)[::-1]
    top_features = np.array(top_features)[sorted_indices]
    top_importances = top_importances[sorted_indices]
    
    # Create a bar plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    sns.set(style="whitegrid")
    ax = sns.barplot(x=top_importances, y=top_features, palette="viridis")
    
    plt.title(title, fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel('Relative Importance', fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('Features', fontsize=12)
    plt.show()

# Assuming the models have already been trained and are named `best_model_ret` and `best_model_grad`

# Get feature importances for retention rate model
importances_ret = best_model_ret.feature_importances_
feature_names = features.columns

# Plot top 10 feature importances for retention rate model
plot_top_10_features(importances_ret, feature_names, 'Top 10 Feature Importances for Retention Rate Model')

# Get feature importances for graduation rate model
importances_grad = best_model_grad.feature_importances_
feature_names = features.columns

# Plot top 10 feature importances for graduation rate model
plot_top_10_features(importances_grad, feature_names, 'Top 10 Feature Importances for Graduation Rate Model')

Part III: Conclusion ¶

Conclusion¶

This project applied machine learning techniques to analyze the College Scorecard data provided by the U.S. Department of Education. The primary objective was to identify key university-level factors that predict strong retention and graduation rates. Here are the key takeaways from the analysis:

  1. Descriptive Analysis: The descriptive analysis provided insights into the distribution of various features such as tuition fees, student demographics, and retention and graduation rates across different types of institutions. It highlighted significant differences between public and private institutions, as well as four-year and less-than-four-year institutions.

  2. Exploratory Analysis: The exploratory analysis helped to identify relationships between various features. For instance, the analysis revealed correlations between financial aid, student demographics, and academic outcomes.

  3. Predictive Modeling: The predictive models were able to effectively predict retention and graduation rates. The LightGBM model was particularly effective due to its ability to handle both numerical and categorical features efficiently.

  4. Feature Importance: The feature importance analysis revealed that institutional characteristics such as retention rates of full-time and part-time students, and demographic factors like the percentage of older undergraduates and independent students, are significant predictors of both retention and graduation rates. Financial factors, such as the percentage of students receiving Pell grants and the median debt of graduates, also played a crucial role.

Key Insights¶

  • Institutional Support: Features related to institutional support, such as faculty salary, percentage of full-time faculty, and financial aid, are critical for both retention and graduation rates. This suggests that institutions with better resources and support systems tend to have better student outcomes.

  • Student Demographics: Demographic factors such as age of entry, percentage of older undergraduates, and percentage of independent students are important predictors. These features highlight the diverse needs of different student populations and the impact of personal and financial challenges on their academic success.

  • Financial Factors: The impact of financial factors like the number of students with debt and the percentage receiving federal loans or Pell grants underscores the importance of financial aid in supporting student retention and graduation.

Future Work¶

Future work could include:

  • Expanding the analysis to include other datasets for a more comprehensive study.
  • Exploring the impact of additional features such as academic support services, extracurricular activities, and student satisfaction surveys.
  • Implementing and comparing more advanced machine learning models to improve predictive performance.

By understanding these key factors, educational institutions can better target their efforts to improve student outcomes and ensure higher rates of retention and graduation. This project demonstrates the power of data analytics and machine learning in uncovering valuable insights from complex educational data.

If you have any questions or would like to discuss this project further, feel free to reach out!
